      <div xml:id="NA344-kiḷavi">
        <p type="edition">itu tōḻi ciṟaippuṟamākat talaimakaṉ kēṭpac colliyatu.</p>
        <p type="translation" xml:lang="en">This is what the confidante said so that HE would hear when he was behind the fence.</p>
        </div>
      <div xml:id="NA344">
        <lg type="edition">
<l>            aṇivarai maruṅki ṉaituvaḷarn tiṭṭa</l>
<l>            maṇiyēr tōṭṭa maiyā rēṉa</l>
<l>            lirumpiṭit taṭakkaiyiṟ ṟaṭaiiya perumpuṉaṅ</l>
<l>            kāval kaṇṇiṉa māyi ṉāyiḻai</l>
<l>            nannilai yiṭaiterin tuṇarāṉ ṟaṉmalai</l>
<l>            yāra nīviya vaṇikiḷa rākañ</l>
<l>            cāra ṉīḷiṭaic cālavaṇ ṭārppac</l>
<l>            celvaṉ celluṅko ṟāṉē yuyarvaraip</l>
<l>            peruṅkal viṭarakañ cilampa virumpuli</l>
<l>            kaḷiṟutolait turaṟuṅ kaṭiyiṭi maḻaicettuc</l>
<l>            centiṉai yuṇaṅka ṟokukku</l>
<l>            miṉkaḷ yāṇarttam muṟaivi ṉūrkkē.</l>
            </lg>
        <lg type="translation" xml:lang="en">
<l rend="indent2">If our eyes [are] guarding, [o you of] choice jewels,</l>
<l rend="indent">            the big field, plump<note place="foot">Actually the <term xml:lang="ta">taṭaiiya</term> is awkwardly positioned. It cannot well apply to the field. To be precise, here it looks rather like a real <term xml:lang="ta">peyareccam</term> (of a defective verb): "the big field on which, as the broad trunk of the large she-elephant, the millet has become plump".</note> as the broad trunk of the large she-elephant,</l>
<l rend="indent">            of millet, full of collyrium, with leaves resembling sapphires(?),</l>
<l rend="indent">            grown [and] planted wonderfully on the decorative mountain side,</l>
<l>        will he be going<note place="foot">Supposedly <term xml:lang="ta">celvaṉ cellum</term> has to be treated as a kind of figura etymologica.</note> himself,</l>
<l rend="indent">            while the bees are humming very much, on the long way to the slope,</l>
<l rend="indent2">            on [his] breast shining with decorations smeared with sandal from</l>
<l rend="indent3">            his mountain, he who does not perceive [and] distinguish our state,</l>
<l>        – to the village of their(?) residence, fertile with sweet toddy,</l>
<l>            where they gather the dried [corn] of the red millet,</l>
<l rend="indent">            thinking it speedily thundering rain when the big tiger, having destroyed</l>
<l rend="indent2">            the elephant bull, roars so that the inside of the cave of big stones</l>
<l rend="indent3">             resounds on the high mountain.<note place="foot">Here the message of the whole seems to be ambiguous. It might either be read as an utterance of HER fear: will HE go while there is still opportunity to meet in the millet field? Or we can see here the poetologically more advanced topos of HIS going to his own place in order to settle the marriage with his people. And then we might even ask whether there was a reading <term xml:lang="ta">celvañ cellum</term>: "will he be going for wealth?"</note></l>
      </lg>
      </div>
    </body>
